                    <div class="subcaption-edit">
                        <h2><em> Figure 1: Cas13a cleavage products have a 5’ hydroxyl and a 2’,3’-cyclic phosphate end. Not final figure, it is just a place holder but it is reproduced from Shigematsu et al. 2018.  </em></h2>
                    <img src="https://2021.igem.org/wiki/images/3/38/T--UCSC--cas13a-cylic-phosphate-ends.png"/>
                    </div>

                    <p> Similar to the type IV CRISPR-Cas system that includes Cas13a, Cas proteins use crRNA to fight invading nucleic acids in the Csm effector pathway. The Cas proteins assemble into a complex and use Cas10 to find and destroy invader sequences. Cas10 also exhibits non-specific cleavage abilities, like Cas13a, that result in cyclic adenylate-signaling molecules that activate a secondary effector molecule Csm6 (Kazlauskiene et al. 2017). Upon activation, Csm6 non-specifically cleaves single stranded RNA (ssRNA) in order to enhance nucleic acid destruction (Niewoehner et al. 2016). </p>

                    <p> Even though Csm6 activation in vivo is by cyclic adenylates produced by Cas10, Kazlauskiene et al. show that linear adenine homopolymers terminated with a 2’,3’-cyclic phosphate (Cas13a cleavage products) are also capable of activating Csm6. SHERLOCKv2 exploits this ability in order to amplify signal detection by cutting more fluorescent reporters, resulting in more fluorescence upon detection of the target sequence.  </p>

